<!-- CONTENT -->
<section class="section-padding">
<div class="container">

<a href="leadership.html" class="back-link">← Back to Leadership</a>

<div class="row align-items-center g-5">

  <!-- IMAGE -->
  <div class="col-lg-5">
    <img src="images/leader5.jpg" alt="Marion Bracy" class="leader-img">
  </div>

  <!-- BIO -->
  <div class="col-lg-7">

    <h2>Biography</h2>

    <p>
      Brother Marion B. Bracy is a lifelong servant leader initiated into Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity, Inc.
      on November 20, 1981, through the Beta Phi Chapter at Dillard University in New Orleans, Louisiana.
    </p>

    <p>
      Early in his fraternity journey, he served on the Southwest Region Election Committee (1982) and Awards Committee (1983),
      which led to his election as Assistant Vice President for the Southwest Region in 1983. Following regional leadership transitions,
      he served as Acting Vice President as an undergraduate brother, managing key administrative responsibilities for the region.
    </p>

    <p>
      His national service expanded under multiple General Presidents, including leadership roles with the College Brother Commission,
      where he later served as Chairman and authored the first College Brothers Advisors Handbook, adopted nationally.
      He also served on key national committees including Elections, Time and Place, and the Headquarters Facility Audit Committee.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 1989, he became the youngest elected President of the Sigma Lambda Chapter. Under his leadership, the chapter launched
      Project Alpha, secured grant funding, and was selected to host the 1993 National Convention. He also led efforts to acquire
      and renovate the Sigma Lambda Alpha House.
    </p>

    <p>
      Professionally, Brother Bracy has over four decades of leadership in higher education facilities management. He has served
      in senior roles at Dillard University and Xavier University of Louisiana, where he played a key role in post-Hurricane Katrina recovery,
      securing over $100 million in FEMA funding and overseeing more than $250 million in capital construction projects.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 2022, he returned to Dillard University as Vice President for Facilities and Real Estate Management, leading major infrastructure
      and student housing projects. His career reflects a sustained legacy of leadership, institutional development, and service.
    </p>

  </div>

</div>

</div>
</section>

